{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_frederick_ver03/data/sn89060127/00279522023/1937111201/0524.xml":{"full_text":"Page 6\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT\nAND\nTHE LEDGER-ENTERPRISE\nPublished Every Friday at Pocomoke City, Maryland.\nEDWARD J. CLARKE, Editor and Owner\n$1.50 The Year In Advance.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Pocomoke City, Maryland, as Second Class Matter\niggg NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nASSOCIATION\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 12, 1937\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nTo put it mildiy, the business outlook today is extremely con\nfused. One one hand, it is predicted that this winter\u2019s domestic\ncommerce will be the best since 1929, with retail sales in some\nlines perhaps exceeding the boom-time figure. On the other, busi\nness leaders are seriously disturbed\u2014and many of them are plain\nly pessimistic as to the trend of future events.\nThis anomaly is easily explained. For in the view of execu\ntives, the short-term outlook is favorable, and the long-term is bad.\nPurchasing power is tied up, farm income is at a six-year high,\nconsumer goods are moving rapidly. Yet, the unrest in Europe,\nthe tangled political situation, at home, including the threat of\nmore government in business, the apparent certainty of higher\ntaxes, the prospect of still more serious labor disturbances, and the\nnervousness of security investors and speculators are retarding\nfactors.\nAs everyone knows, the stock market took its biggest drop in\nyears a few weeks ago. Values are far below their spring and ear\nly summr levels. And while the stock market is not necessarily\nan accurate barometer of actual business conditions, it does pretty\nclosely reflect the views of finance on both big and small levels,\nand represents credit, capital and reserve spending power. Ex\nplanations of the drop varied, and disclosed the opposed schools of\nthought now in existence. Stock market officials ascribed the col\nlapse as being due mainly to excessively strict regulating by the\nSEC, which has largely eliminated speculative operators who in\nthe past could be trusted to take up much of the slack in thin mar\nkets. Government officials, such as SEC head James Landis, who\nhas recently resigned to become Dean of Law at Harvard, defend\ned the regulatory policy, intimated that still more stringent regu\nlaions may be necessary. Whether the Landis\u2019 point of view is\nright or wrong, such a policy evidently has a dampening effect on\nlarge industry.\nSo far as the political situation is concerned, all is gone. Presi\ndent Roosevelt's sweep around the country, in the view of most\ncommentators, is designed to give him a chance to meet and see\npeople, to use his personality, and to enlist public support in his\ncampaign against the conservative wing of his party. The Presi\ndent, as he has said in almost so many words, is now envisioning a\n\u201csecond New Deal\u201d which involves still further enlarging Federal\nauthority, new and restrictive legislation dealing with business\npractices, notably in the field of wages and hours, and a lessening\nof the power of the Federal judiciary.\nEvidence is not lacking that Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s popular follow\ning has diminished\u2014the Black Ku Klux Klan disclosures are per\nhaps the most serious blow he has received. But it cannot yet be\nsaid with accuracy that a majority of the voters are no longer\nwilling to follow his lead.\nIn some quarters it appears that war scares have been exag\ngerated\u2014and in others they have been too much minimized. A\nmajor war could not help but tremendously affect American indus\ntry, whether we become involved as belligerents or not. General\nexpert view is that there will be no war next year\u2014but that there\nwi| be one in 1939, when Europe\u2019s vast rearmament program is\nmore or less completed. American foreign policy has so for been\ncareful, even timid\u2014as it must. We are in the delicate position\nof attempting to keep clear of war\u2014yet having to maintain our\nprestige in the interest of American citizens and residents abroad.\nHot-heads criticize Secretary Hull for what they think is vacilla\ntion. Cooler heads generally approve his policy, think that he is\nright in seeking to feel our way gently and carefully.\nThere is talk of anentirely new gross earnings tax on business.\nThis, coming on top of the present corporation income tax, the\nprofits and loss levy, the surplus tax and other taxes, might make\nit impossible for business to maintain expected dividends, even in\na time of heavy orders. There is no organized movement behind\npolicy, and about the continued government deficits which will re\nsuch a tax, howver. Business is worried about the general tax\nquire heavy new taxes of some kind\u2014unless an unlooked-for re\ntrenchment in government spending occurs.\nIn conclusion, it should be pointed out that some experts\nfeel that the present business recession is less important than it\nseems, that the political and tax situation will work out without\ndoing too much damage. Best guess is: The short-term outlook\nfor commerce is favorable, and the long-term outlook is in the laps\nof the gods.\nHIGHWAYS OF TOMORROW\nCompared to the roads of a generation ago, modem highways\nare marvels of excellence. Yet, in spite of this phenomenal devel\nopment, today\u2019s system is woefully inadequate, as Frank T. Sheets\npoints out in an article in Public Safety.\n\u201cProgressive strides have been taken and must continue to be\ntaken in driver education and in providing safety regulation for\nvehicles,\u201d says Mr. Sheets, \u201cbut the ultimate in traffic conven\nience and safety will not be reached until we actually provide ade\nquate highways and build safety into them.\u201d\nToday\u2019s engineers have designed tomorrow\u2019s highways. These\nmagnificent roads will include terminal facilities in cities where\nby traffic will move to various points with a minimum of conges\ntion; main super highways of many lanes, with divisions in the\ncenter to prevent head-on collisions, will carry cross-country traf\nfic, avoiding congested areas enroute; Intermediate highways will\nserve local traffic needs'; even the lowest grade, little-used roads\nwill be given some cheap form of all-weather surface; arterial ur\nban streets will carry into and through cities and towns that part\nof rural main trunk traffic which has business in the metropolitan\narea.\nThis seems a far off ideal, but not long ago the automobile, the\nradio, the airplane, the telephone seemed so, too. The cost of de\nveloping highways and streets of maximum safety on a national\nscale, will be tremendous\u2014but it will be spent over a long period\nof time and no form of expenditure by government can better serve\nthe people. Better highways are not a cure-all for the accident prob\nlem \u2014but when we develop our roads to the point where the chance\nof accidents is educed to a minimum, a long step toward lowering\nour ghastly annual toll of deaths will be taken.\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAND\nAnnual Meet Scouts\nConference On Wed.\nContinued from Page 1\nbers.\nColonel William B. Tilghman, Jr.,\nSalisbury, was in charge of arrange\nmen; John W. Noble, Easton, attend\nance; Mr. Fowler, program; Ralph A.\nRoss, Pocomoke City, morale; and Mr.\nSolomon, exhibits.\nDuring an optional period at 5:45\no\u2019clock, colored motion pictures of the\nRodney scout camps were shown in\nthe auditorium and a meeting of coun\ncil executive board members to receive\nreports of discussion groups was\nscheduled.\nThose present from Pocomoke, be\nsides Scout Master Henderson and his\n\u201cplaylet\u201d boys, were: Ralph A. Ross,\nWilliam H. Walters, Jr., E. W. Ham,\nRaymond C. Dryden and Edward J.\nClarke.\nURGE ATTENDANCE AT\nDOG FIELD COMPETITION\nWith 400 persons in attendance, 30\namateur and professional bird dogs,\npaired in 16 braces, which flushed\nmore than 20 quail, competed in the\nfirst annual Worcester County field\ntrials on Monday last on the Paul M.\nJones farm at Public Landing.\nThe trials were staged by the Wor\ncester County Fish and Game Pro\ntective Association of which Arthur\nW. Duer, Snow Hill is president. M.\nE. Watson, Salisbury, was secretary\nof the trials and the judges were:\nFrank Shirven, of Chestertown and E.\nC. Curtis, of New Jersey.\nDogs were entered from Accomack\nCounty, Va.; Easton, Salisbury, Poco\nmoke City, Berlin, Ocean City and\nCrisfield.\nFour winners were presented awards\nas follows:\nFirst\u2014Joe, setter dog, Roy Gordy,\nSnow Hill; second, Dot Speckles,\npointer bitch, W. E. Boole, Pocomoke\nCity; third, Specks Hayward, setter\ndog, Thomas Watson Hayward and\nPhillip Lewis, Salisbury; fourth, Miss\nRasco, setter bitch, M. E. Watson, Sal\nisbury; fifth, Ned, pointer pup, Mrs.\nZadia Henry Murgerd, Berlin.\nGrandma always was a keen shopper and quick to \"snap up** a bargain\nbut you\u2019ll recognize these BARGAIN OFFERS without her years of ex\nperience you save real money... you get a swell selection of magazines\nand a full year of our newspaper. That\u2019s what we call a \"break** for you\nreaders... no wonder grandma says\u2014\"YOU\u2019VE GOT SOMETHING THERE!**\nthis NEWSPAPER-1 FULL YEAR...AND ALL\nANY THREE MAGAZINES IN THIS LIST\n(CHECK 3 MAGAZINES AND RETURN WITH COUPON)\n]jl] \u2022JE OAmerican Fruit Grower\u2014l yr. \u25a1Home Friend lyr.\n\u25a0dBwUULLIJ American Poultry Jouraal-lyr. DHome Am Needlecraft 1 yr. ANIY\nGazette 2yr*. DHouseholdMagazine 1 yr. WnLI\nHHSPlmnnlslnfi n J Leghorn World lyr.\nHOUSEHOLD \u00b0aove r teafAm Rev,ew l l J\u00a3 Mother\u2019s Home Life lyr.\noSSSJuS3\u201dzrrrIJS: W>\u20144Th\n\u25a1Gentlewoman Magazine _lyr. \u25a1Rhode Island Red Journal-1 yr. fJ ftj M\nOGood Stories lyr. \u25a1Plymouth Rock Monthly_l yr. M EX4\nwGta i Home Clide i y Successful Farming 1 yr. w\n\u25a1Capper's Farmer 1 yr. \u25a1Woman\u2019s World 1 yr.\nI THIS NEWSPAPER-1 FULL YEAR AND 4 MAGAZINES I\nGROUP A\u2014S*l.ci 2 1 GROUP B-Mml 2 W\n\u25a1American Boy 8 mot. \u25a1American Fruit Grower 1 yr. __ _\n*,l J 1. B \u25a1McCall's Magazine lyr. \u25a1American Poultry Journal-1 yr. AL\nMMSMSMIiMMffI Christian Herald 6 mot. S 5f e 1 \u201c';5f tette Jn- __\nif \u25a1Parents\u2019Magazine 6mos. Blade* Ledger lyr. C\nWiKiiiaHy DPathfinder (Weekly) lyr.\nc trial Review lyr. HSwjouLd -1 y\u00a3 ONLY\nVT*VJ\\LLS \u25a1RomanticStories lyr. DGoodStories L\u2014lyr. VIS 1.1\nOSilaer Screen lyr. \u25a1Home Arts Needlecraft lyr.\nSrhhX' \u25a1Screen Bnolr Iy> DHome Friend lyr.\nDTrue Confessions lyr. DHousehold Magazine lyr.\nJjJwgaaKp SS-frf.<?->\u2014BmS*\u201c.HSSfficrri\u00a3 \u00a3#if/}\nDHome Arts Needlecraft 2 yrs. Woman\u2019s World 1 yr.\nhome offer VTFnnTrR!TT!!THTITV7Trn\nTHIS NEWSPAPER\u2014I YEAR A|_|_ e 4\nMr-Toll*. t\u2014 Ploose clip list of magazines after checking one* desired,\nn SOIO\nGood Stories 1 yr. Gentlemen: I enclose lam checking below the\nFarm Journal 1 yr. offerdesired with a year's subscription to your paper.\nDBIG VALUE OFFER OTHB QUALITY OFFER\nSTORY OFFER DTHE HOME OFFER DTHB STORY OFFER\nTHIS NEWSPAPER-1 YEAR\nTrue Story lyr. HLL 3 Name\nsash \u2014;y *925\nCountry Homel yr. a\u2014 R.F.D State\nWorcester Democrat\nLate Potato Growers\nWarned To Check Seed\nLate potato growers in Worcester\nCounty are warned to check up on\ntheir seed since it has been dug to\ndetermine whether or not the tubers\nare rotting in storage. While some\nfields were entirely free of late\nblight, others were badly infested. A\nnumber of cases have been reported\nto the County Agent which, after in\nvestigation, showed that the seed\nshould be rigidly culled out, taking\nout the rotting tubers. Some growers\nhave already had to cull out almost\nhalf of their seed, due to late blight\ninfestation.\nRotted seed is the main damage\nwhich late blight will cause. It is\nnot transmitted into next year\u2019s crop.\nGrowers who have stored their seed\nin kilns are advised especially to check\nup on the presence of rot.\nDelegation From M. E.\nChurch Goes To Delmar\nContinued from page 1\nthere was a roll call of the leagues\nrepresented. The local league with a\ndelegation of thirty members were the\nhappy winners of the seventy-two inch\nLeague Banner, given to the league\nhaving the largest group present bas\ned on the percentage of membership\nand the distance traveled to the con-;\nvention. After the roll call the var-j\nious discussion groups, under thej\nleadership of different ministers, j\nsought to solve some of the problems'\nwith which the youth of today is con-!\nfronted. Following the discussioh, Dr.\nJ. W. Rowland, editor of the Rich\nmond Christian Advocate, gave a very\ninteresting talk on \u201cThe Garden of\nYouth.\u201d\nThe climax of the afternoon session\nwas the Holy Communion, when the\nassembled youth reaffirmed their faith\nin the Lord Jesus Christ and knelt\nat the foot of a lighted cross in a\nprayer rededicating their lives to\nChristian service. This Holy Com\nmunion at twilight and prayer of con\nsecration has been spoken of by many\nas being the most touching sight they\nhad ever witnessed.\nIn the evening the guests gathered\nin the church dining room for the\nbanquet presided over by Rev. Vaughn\nMore, of Cape Charles, Virginia, as\ntoastmaster, who filed his post to the\ngreat enjoyment of all. The first\nspeaker of the evening, Rev. F. Reid\nIsaac, Superintendent of the Straw\nbridge Home for Boys, Inc., spoke on\nMissions and reminded the Leaguers\nof their motto, that as they \u201cLook Up,\nLift Up.\u201d\nDr. J. J. Bunting, Superintendent\nof the Salisbury District, spoke in\nglowing terms of the Salem League,\nsaying that it was one of the most\nactive in the District. In his stirring\naddress, he challenged the youth to\ntake advantage of the conditions at\nhand for out of every depression and\ntroublous times as these, people of\ngreatness have grown.\nThe youth came away from that\nconvention enriched by the Christian\nfellowship and with a clearer concep\ntion of the work which the Epworth\nLeagues of the Salisbury District are\ndoing.\nThe Salem League came home with\nthe banner and proud of the reputa\ntion they had won as a league and\npeldging themselves to even greater\nattainments throughout the coming\nyear.\nDR. R. I. GIVENS\nDENTIST\nOffice over New Callahan\nBuilding\nPhone\u20143l3\nCLAIBORNE ANNAPOLIS\nMATAPEAKE FERRIES\nSave 100 Miles\nFALL SCHEDULE\nEffective September 28th, 1937\nDAILY SUNDAY (E. S. T.)\nBetween Annapolis and Matapeake\nLEAVE LEAVE\nANNAPOLIS MATAPEAKE\n8:00 a. m. 7:25 a. m\n10:00 a. m. 9:00 a. m\n11:00 a. m. 11:00 a. m.\n12:00 noon 12:00 noon\n1:00 p. m. 1:00 p. nt.\n2:00 p. m. 2:00 p. m\n3:00 p. m. 3:00 p. m.\n4:00 p. m. 4:00 p. m.\n6:00 p. m. 5:00 p. m\n8:00 p. m. 7:00 p. m\nBetween Annapolis and Claiborne\nLEAVE LEAVE\nANNAPOLIS CLAIBORNE\n7:30 a. m. 9:30 a. m\n5:00 p. m. 7:00 p. m\nThe Claiborne-Annapolis Ferry Co.\nANNAPOLIS. MD.\nMISCELLANEOUS\n\nt NOTICE\u2014This is to notify the pub\nl lie that I will not be responsible for\nany bills contracted by any person\nother than myself. Harry Phillips.\nNov. 12-ltp.\nNOTICE\u2014 HAULING, moderate\nprices. Call Edwin Martin, 710 Sec\nond St., Phone 221-J.\nc Oct. 29-4 t.\n1\nHave you a figure fault? A Spen\nt cer foundation garment created for\nyou will correct it and give improved\nhealth, style and posture. See Mrs.\nW. B. Rock, 118 Sixth St., Pocomoke.\nOct. 8-tf\n1\nf DR. G. E. FlNNEY\u2014Graduate Lie\nensed Veterinarian. Onancock, Va\nt Phone 168. Aug.-27-tf\n1 a F et HurtJ Groh\u2019a Sponge Rubber\nArch Supports relieves tired aching\ni calloused feet. For comfort Phone\n8 l? 8 Y or Mr. Groh.\nMarch 19-tf.\n1 NOTICE\u2014Price on hair catting\n26 cents will remain the same\n1 Shaws.\nr July 10-tf\n1 DISSOLUTION OF PARTNERSHIP\nNotice is hereby given that the\npartnership heretofore existing be\ntween Harold C. Lambertson and Mar\nion P. Lambertson, trading as \u201cLam\nbertson\u2019s\u201d or \u201cLambertsons\u2019 engag\ned in the business of retail grocers\nlocated at the comer of Clarke Ave\nnue and Walnut Street, in Pocomoke\nCity, Worcester County, Maryland,\nwas dissolved by mutual consent on\nthe ninth day of November, 1937, Mr.\nMarion P. Lambertson retiring from\nthe business. Mr. Harold C. Lambert\nson will continue the business in his\nown name, as sole owner, at the same\nlocation, and will assume the out\nstanding liabilities, and is entitled to\ncollect all outstanding accounts due to\nthe partnership.\nHAROLD C. LAMBERTSON\nMARION P. LAMBERTSON\nWitness as to Harold C. Lambertson:\nLolita R. Smith\nWitness as to Marion P. Lambertson:\nLolita R. Smith\nNov. 12-\nPublic Sale\nOF VALUABLE\nPersonal Property\nHaving decided to discontinue farm\ning I will sell at public auction on my\nfarm near Pocomoke 2% miles east\nof Dryden Milling Co., on\nThurs. Nov. 18, 1937\nBeginning at 10 o\u2019clock A. M.\nA he *T fo,lowing P ro P er ty to wit: Three\nA No. 1 Mules, weighing 1000 to 1100\nlbs.; all harness; fifty-eight 8-foot\nPotato bed frames; barrel spray;\ntransplanter; upright piano; 2 large\nbrooder stoves, good as new; and\nmany other things too numerous to\nmention.\nTERMS: Made known day of sale.\nGEORGE C. BAYLIS\nxr Pocomoke City, Md.\nNov. 12-lt.\nPublic Sale\nOF Furniture\nTea Room Opposite Theatre\nSat. Nov. 20th\nBginning 10 o\u2019clock A. M.\nTerms\u2014Cash\n7 double beds, springs, mattresses;\n4 single beds, springs, mattresses; 1\nday bed, mattress; 10 bureaus; 4 wash\nstands; 1 chiffonier; 10 rockers; 10\nchairs; 2 desks; 6 piece living room\nsuite; 8 rugs, 9x12; 1 glider; 6 porch\nchairs; 3 breakfast suites; 3 tables;\n1 double coal oil heater (new); 2\nsingle coal oil heaters; 2 double spear\nheaters; 1 range stove; 4 wood stoves;\n2 ice boxes; 1 coal oil stove. Other\narticles.\npObOc sale\nOF VALUABLE\nPERSONALTY\nHaving decided to discontinue farm\ning, I will sell at public auction on\nthe premises where I now reside,\nknown as the Churn Farm, about 3\nmiles from Pocomoke City on the\nCedar Hall Road.\nTUES., NOVEMBER 16\nat 10 o\u2019clock A. M.\nthe following personal property, to\nwit:\nOne pair mules, 3 and 4 years old;\n1 middle aged mule; 1 horse cart; 1\nwagon; 1 riding cultivator; 1 2-way\nriding plow; and other farm utensils\nto numerous to mention.\nTerms of SaIe\u2014CASH.\nCATHELL F. POWELL\nAuctioneer: J. S. Melvin.\nNov. 5-2 t.\nWhen you have something to sell.\nrent or trade run an ad in our Class\ndied Columns.\nFriday, Novem\u00dfer 12,1937\nClassified Advertising\nI\"\nj All Classified Advertising is charge\ned at 2 cents per word. Cash or\nstamps must accompany all orders,\ne No ad taken for less than 25 cents.\nCHURCH NOTICES\n1 BAKE!\u2014Gas office. Nov. .20. M.\nP. Church.\nNov. 12-2 t.\ni.\nWANTED\nWANTED\u2014MiddIe aged woman\nwants work doing plain housekeeping.\nt Winnie Mariner, Atlantic, Va.\nNov. 12-ltp.\nt _____________\nI WANTED\u2014A good range cook\nt stove, bum wood or coal. Worcester\nDemocrat.\nNov. 12-3tp.\nRawleigh\u2019s famous everyday house\nhold necessities in increasing demand.\nSales way up this year. Cash in on\nthis opportunity supplying consumers.\nNo matter what you have done in the\npast here is your chance. Good open\nings nearby. Should start earning\ni S3O weekly; increase every month.\nRawleigh\u2019s, Dept. MDK-98-E, Chester,\nPa.\nNov. 12-ltp.\nFOR SALE\nTURKEYS FOR SALE\u2014Toms, 25c,\nhens, 28c.Mrs. E. W. Mills.\nNov. 12-2tp.\nJ FOR SALE CHEAP\u2014One Estate\nHeatrola in excellent condition. Can\nbe seen at C. W. Bunting\u2019s shop or\nCrystal Restaurant.\nNov. 12-tf\n\n1 FOR SALE\u2014Dining room suites\nbedroom suite, feather bed, large size\nbeveled edge mirror. Arthur M. Mc-\nDaniel.\n1 Nov. 12-4tp.\nFOR SALE!\u2014R. C. A. Radio in per\nfect condition. Price SIO.OO. Mrs.\nMark Callahan, Pocomoke.\nNov. 121tp.\nI FOR SALE\u2014Dining table and six\nchairs, bargain price. Mrs. A. S. Ven\nable, 303 Second St.\nNov. 5-2tp\nFOR SALE!\u2014Dining room suite.\nMrs. W. H. Pope, Clarke Ave., ext.\nNov. 5-3tp.\nFOR SALE OR RENT\u2014House oa\nMarket St. Possesion at once. Apply\nWorcester Democrat or write Charles\nLee Hall, Pine Bush, New York, Route\n1. Will sell for $2,000.\nNov. 5-3tp.\nFOR SALE\u2014Wooden ventilator,\nreasonable. Cora Powell, Front St.\nNov. 5-2tp.\n3 BROODER STOVES FOR SALE\nCheap. Have been used only about f\nweeks. Apply Worcester Democrat.\nOct. 1-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014A large assortment of\nused Oil and Gasoline Stoves at bar\ngain prices. Eastern Shore Gas Co.,\nPocomoke 12-2-tf.\nFOR RENT\nAPARTMENT FOR RENT\u2014Now\noccupied by Mrs. Margaret Burroughs.\nPossession December 1. Apply W.\nSidney Stevens.\nNov. 12tf.\n3-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath\u20144o6 Laurel St.\nNov. 12-tf\nFOR RENT\u2014S-room house with\nmodem conveniences and garage. Ap\nply to 704 Second St.\nNov. 12-tf.\nFOR RENT\u2014Modem 4-room apart\nment with lights and bath. Dr. N. E.\nSartorius.\nNov 5-tf.\nHOUSE FOR RENT\u20146I4 Walnnt\nSt. Possession at once. Mrs. W. S.\nEllis, Crisfield.\nNov. 5-2tp.\nFOR RENT\u20143 nice furnished rooms\n218 Laurel St.\nOct. 29-3tp.\nFOR RENT\u2014First floor 4-room\napartment. Also a second floor 4-room\napartment. Apply to S. A. Evans.\nOct. 22-tf.\nAPARTMENT FOR RENT\u2014Apply\nAllen D. Merrill Bros.\nOct. 22-tf.\nFOR RENT\u2014B-room dwelling. Ap-\nply to S. A. Evans, Pocomoke City,\nMd.\nOct. 8-tf\nFOR RENT\u20144 or 5-room apart\nment, good location, water and lights.\nApply Worcester Democrat.\nOct. 1-tf\n5-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath. Henrietta Chatham.\nSept. 24-tf.\nAPARTMENT FOR RENT\u2014Fur\nnished or unfurnished. 105 Laurel St,\nSept. 24-tf.\n\u201cnotice\nWhen in need of building material\nsee me. I am now equipped to fur\nnish at the mill or deliver lumber in\nthe rough. Also slab wood $2.00 per\ncord at mill. Will deliver at reason\nable additional price. Phone 2 F 13.\nW. V. TAYLOR\nR. D. 1 Pocomoke\n